======================================================================
PART 4: WHAT IS GOING WRONG? CHORDLESS VS ALL CYCLES
======================================================================

KEY QUESTION: Does the OCF use CHORDLESS odd cycles or ALL odd cycles?

The definition says 'directed odd cycles' — which could mean:
  (a) All directed odd cycles (including those with chords)
  (b) Only CHORDLESS directed odd cycles

Testing both interpretations at n=5:
  T0: H=5
    Chordless: 2 cycles, I(2)=5, I(-1)=-1, alpha=[1, 2]
    All:       2 cycles, I(2)=5, I(-1)=-1, alpha=[1, 2]
    Match chordless? True  Match all? True

  T1: H=11
    Chordless: 4 cycles, I(2)=9, I(-1)=-3, alpha=[1, 4]
    All:       5 cycles, I(2)=11, I(-1)=-4, alpha=[1, 5]
    Match chordless? False  Match all? True

  T2: H=9
    Chordless: 3 cycles, I(2)=7, I(-1)=-2, alpha=[1, 3]
    All:       4 cycles, I(2)=9, I(-1)=-3, alpha=[1, 4]
    Match chordless? False  Match all? True

  T3: H=13
    Chordless: 4 cycles, I(2)=9, I(-1)=-3, alpha=[1, 4]
    All:       5 cycles, I(2)=11, I(-1)=-4, alpha=[1, 5]
    Match chordless? False  Match all? False

  T4: H=5
    Chordless: 2 cycles, I(2)=5, I(-1)=-1, alpha=[1, 2]
